Hi,

I noticed that String.IndexOf(String) is extremely slow compared to V8 (90 times faster), OpenJDK 13 (270 times faster) and my own naive IndexOf implementation on the same .NET Core version (250 times faster).

It's .NET Core 3.1.100-preview1-014459 on macOS 10.15.
.NET Core 3.0 has the same issue.

```C#

static int TestDotNetIndexOf()
{
    const int N = 1_000_000;
    var count = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i)
    {
        var s = i.ToString();
        if (s.IndexOf("999") != -1)
        {
            ++count;
        }
    }

    return count;
}
```

It's obviously a trvial micro benchmark that comes with all the usual caveats, but that doesn't explain a two orders of magnitude performance difference. I did print the result of the test function in all implementations to make sure the code is actually executed.

You might suspect that int.ToString() could be the culprit as well, but it's not.

```csharp
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
struct NonBlittable
{
    bool _nonBlittable;
}

[DllImport("Unused")]
private static extern void PointerToNonBlittableType(NonBlittable* pNonBlittable, string unused);
```

Calling above method will throw a `MarshalDirectiveException` because pointers to nonblittable structs cannot be marshalled across the p/invoke boundary.

But dropping the `string unused` argument will make the p/invoke work. That looks like a bug that makes it look like it's okay to take dependency on non-blittable managed layout on the native side.

~~Making this throw is likely compat-breaking.~~

